<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Alright, you're right, I'm not into hockey, 80-100 is a bit of an exaggeration. However the fact remains that she didn't get out of the way, and you're more willing to blame this girl for dying then a franchise who had to know it was dangerous to not have netting, but did nothing about it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Hockey as a pro sport has beenarounf for well over 50 years. In that 50 years this is MAYBE the second time anyone has died due toa puck flying into the stands. Saying they know it's dangerous is silly. Of course they know it's dangerous, that's why the release of liability is on the back of the tickets. It's just like Auto Racing, the stadium, nor the racing teams and drivers involved are not responsible of something flys off one of the cars and in to the stands and severes your head from your body. <br>
<br>
This was/is and should always be considered a freak accident. There is no controlling the puck if it goes ricocheting off of someone's stick. That's like trying to control the flight path of a baseball midflight. <br>
<br>
Your comparison of the car slamming in to you to this is irrelevant. The car accident could have been stopped before it even happened via more training etc.<br>
<br>
I honestly don't think putting up a net could have stopped this, much the same way that putting up a net at a baseball park will not always stop the ball from going in to the stands. <br>
